## FINAL VERDICT

### Scorecard

| Dimension | Score |
|---|---|
| **Architecture Quality** | 7.5 / 10 |
| **UI Quality** | 9 / 10 |
| **Business Logic Quality** | 6 / 10 |
| **Data Integrity** | 5.5 / 10 |
| **Overall Completion** | 78% |
| **Commercial Readiness** | 55% |

### Commentary

**Architecture Quality — 7.5/10**
The reducer pattern is clean. Append-only ledger is correct. Migration system is real engineering. `getInvoiceOutstanding` as a derived selector instead of a mutated field is architecturally sound. Deductions: the 2,669-line monolithic store, `dispatch` exposed publicly on context (bypasses all guards), and several useMemo dependency omissions.

**UI Quality — 9/10**
Genuinely excellent. Better than Vyapar. Better than Marg. The 3-panel POS, expandable rows, skeleton loaders, toast system, and role-based visibility are production-quality. One point off for hardcoded print content and the Finance module having no visible page.

**Business Logic Quality — 6/10**
The core invoice/payment/return flows are correct. But: profit uses live cost (broken), revenue ignores returns (wrong), supplier outstanding doesn't reflect purchase returns (wrong), void invoice over-restores stock when returns exist (wrong). These are not edge cases — they happen in daily operation.

**Data Integrity — 5.5/10**
The backup silently omits 5 critical collections. The `customer.debt` cache has multiple paths to go stale. One dashboard useMemo dependency is wrong. The void+return stock bug is a ghost inventory generator.

